Georgia 🇺🇸 #voteforyourdaughter 

The choice of Walker vs Warnock affects far more then a power dynamic of Republican vs Democrat in the Senate. This election will directly affect the rights, healthcare and bodily autonomy of women and girls in Georgia.

Last week, the Georgia Supreme Court reinstated the state’s ban on abortion after six weeks of pregnancy. Walker calls for a “no-exception” ban. He is not qualified to be a Senator let alone be elected to “represent” or champion women’s rights.

And if you don’t live in Georgia, why does this matter? In the case of a proposed national ban (which the elected Georgia Senator would vote on) even if you live in a “blue” state that has protected women’s reproductive freedoms, you could still be in jeopardy with a national ban. A win by Walker could give the Republicans the votes they need to pass the first step towards a national ban.

#vote #georgia #warnock womensrights #voteforyourdaughter #reproductiverights #publicart #policy #installationart #popart #fearless #forher

Did you know that the National Museum of Women in the Arts @womeninthearts is reopening in the fall? 
Did you know that it’s the ONLY museum in the world devoted to #womeninthearts 

While the museum has been closed for renovations they have treated the exterior with the work of some amazing artists (including DC’s own @misschelove 🧡) and now a massive needle point piece titled SOLANGE created by Austrian artist @katharinacibulka 

Thank you to the museum for making sure to use the exterior as a canvas for public art so important work like this can be seen by so many.

A Happy Birthday toast to a great Washingtonian Mr. Oliver Carr Jr❤️💙 
Happy Birthday to an amazing man,a living legend and visionary in business,real estate and community development. 
Mr. Carr is an inspirational and integral part of our community and a perfect example of how one person can make a huge impact in their own community and beyond. 

I’ve had the honor of working with Mr. Carr for the past five years on one of his properties and monuments of hospitality; The Willard Intercontinental 
@willard_intercontinentaldc 

I’m pretty sure he’s not on Instagram, but I think everybody in Washington DC should raise a toast to Mr. Carr  tonight. You may not know him, but Washington DC is a better place because of him.

North Carolina law now bans nearly all abortions after 20 weeks of pregnancy.
Why is it ok that government, not doctors OR the individual can make decisions and restrictions over women’s bodies and access to health care???

This could be triggering for some folks but  I have a few thoughts about our allegiance to a flag that was adopted in 1777 at the time representing 13 Stars and Stripes and a “new union”.

I’m of the opinion (perhaps unpopular) that we should consider a new design, one that is more dynamic, colorful, representative and celebratory of our nation🌈 of blended cultures.
I am a proponent of color and it’s profound power to communicate unspoken beliefs. 
Perhaps limiting our representation to red and blue sets us up for a choice of one vs the other in our political parties and our interactions .  Color is a powerful story teller and maybe we should consider the impact of a flag of conflict vs community…  what do you think? 

More on this topic and more flags coming soon.

#flag #iplegeallegiancetocolor #america #americathebeautiful #color #popart #popartist #artistofinstagram #dcartist #madeindc

A year ago we prototyped a public art installation concept called #voteforyourdaughter creating statues from my paintings. A year later we are ready to launch #voteforyourdaughter A national public art exhibition and campaign to include 50 artists from 50 states creating 3D statues representing the rights of women and girls in each state. 

I believe art can create connections and conversations that might be too hard to have otherwise. I believe Art is diplomacy we need right now as it can stoke civic engagement, awareness and give people a reason to vote for something. 

Join me at the kick off and fundraiser is next Tuesday Nov 14!  Go to voteforyourdaughter.com  to RSVP and learn more about how to get involved .

It feels soooooo good to put ideas in to action. 
I believe you have to do what you can do, where you are, with what you have.

I’m an artist and I’m from Washington, D.C.

I believe deeply in the power of art as diplomacy.

A vote for your daughter is a vote for her liberties and her freedom. It’s a vote for her healthcare. It’s a vote for her safety. It’s a vote for her education. It’s a vote for her equal pay.

A public art exhibition of this scale cannot happen on its own. There’s a million ways to get involve. We just need you to commit to one.

Follow us at @voteforyourdaughter or go to voteforyourdaughter.com and see how you can get involved.

✨ encourage voter turnout

So many great projects in 2023. This piece will make you look and 🤔  It was one of the largest commissions of the year for RMR group hanging proudly in the lobby of a building near Union Station. A twelve foot triptych of #unionstation made completely of construction documents👀 and gold leaf ⚡️. 
This piece is a nod to the methodology of planning and the time consuming process to design, build and develop real estate in this town.

A special thanks to @tumbldrylow for leading this very detailed and tedious project in the studio.

January 6 was a dark day in our 🇺🇸 history. My heart goes out to everyone involved and affected from the events of that day. 
 The events ushered in the threat of authoritarianism and the potential for dictatorship to our doorstep. 
Many other countries in the world have suffered this same blow and we should learn from their example.
Democracy is fragile because the very spirit requires compromise and progress. It’s not easy when we are so divided and the “truth” of our information is customized to our prejudices. 

“Everybody counts in applying democracy. And there will never be a true democracy until every responsible and law-abiding adult in it, without regard to race, sex, color or creed has his or her own inalienable and unpurchasable voice in government.”
Carrie Chapman Catt
